A starship plugin seems like a really interesting use case! Are you able to save state? or would it be a full execution every time? I've been trying to time different implementations and currently the original version I posted took 9ms on my pc. I then tried this (which I believe is what you were saying) let process = connection.processes().into_iter() .filter(|p| p.name() == "Spotify.exe") (9 more lines were trimmed) This took 12ms which went against what I was expecting (I was expecting it to be faster). My guess is that iterating through all the processes might be much slower than simply looking through all the windows? Not sure. Lastly, I tried a situation where you could theoretically store state and thus store the window id but this also took around 9ms. use window_titles::windows::Window; use winapi::shared::windef::HWND; (2 more lines were trimmed) I would've thought this would have been the quickest considering there's absolutely no iteration at all. At this point I'm wondering if I'm just measuring commands wrong (I'm not used to Windows unfortunately).
I think caching is better, or store state or whatever. And rust security is flagging this as a vulnerability. Any ideas?
